challenging philosophical issues of Western science. In The Politics of Pain Medicine: A Rhetorical-Ontological Inquiry, S. Scott Graham offers a rich and detailed exploration of the medical rhetoric surrounding pain medicine. Graham chronicles the work of interdisciplinary pain management specialists to found a new science of pain and a new approach to pain medicine grounded in a more comprehensive biospychosocial model. His insightful analysis demonstrates how these materials ultimately shape the healthcare community’s understanding of what pain medicine is, how the medicine should be practiced and regulated, and how practitioner-patient relationships are best managed. It is a fascinating, novel examination of one of the most vexing issues in contemporary medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMedicine, Psychosomatic. 0aPain medicine. 0aPainxTreatmentxPsychological aspects. 0aPainxTreatment. 0aPsychophysiology. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  amedicine, medical, treatment, science, scientific communication, communications laboratory, chronic, pain, relief, debilitating, disability, patients, body, physical, psychology, physiology, anesthesia, chiropractor, rhetoric, language, interdisciplinary, healthcare, psychophysiology, treatments, time, experience, understanding, ontology, philosophy, existence, reality, comprehension, metaphysics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226264196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226264196/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles